  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2259853981" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2259853981" />
    <a title="Lilo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19470614-lilo"><img alt="Lilo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1366528768p2/19470614.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2259853981?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lilo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lilo" href="/user/show/19470614-lilo">Lilo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">everyone interested in preserving the U.S. as a democracy, everyone interested to avoid a WWIII</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19470614-lilo?shelf=current-affairs">current-affairs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19470614-lilo?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19470614-lilo?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19470614-lilo?shelf=history-in-the-making">history-in-the-making</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2259853981" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2944332304260588372">Today, April 29, 2018, I finished reading the above book. So this is now the completed, updated version of my review. If you have already read my preliminary review, please don’t miss reading the update following the initial text.<br/><br/><br/>This book has been criticized for being sloppily written and consisting mainly of unproven rumors. Well, I definitely have read books of higher literary value. I could not honestly say that I like the writing style of this book. There are lots of badly constructed, conv</span>
  <span id="freeText2944332304260588372" style="display:none">Today, April 29, 2018, I finished reading the above book. So this is now the completed, updated version of my review. If you have already read my preliminary review, please don’t miss reading the update following the initial text.<br /><br /><br />This book has been criticized for being sloppily written and consisting mainly of unproven rumors. Well, I definitely have read books of higher literary value. I could not honestly say that I like the writing style of this book. There are lots of badly constructed, convoluted sentences. And I am sure that any strict English teacher would need a lot of red ink proofreading this book. However, HOWEVER, I cannot thank the author enough for writing this book. He has done America and its allies a big service. (“A known danger is half a danger.”)<br /><br />Don’t we all deserve to learn what is happening to our country? Shouldn’t we all be made aware that the present President of the United States, the supposed-to-be Leader of the Free World, is not only ethically and morally unfit for the job but apparently an outright imbecile with the attention span of a preschooler? You might think that you already know this, but believe you me: It is worse than you can imagine. I have watched the daily news all along and tried to keep myself informed, but this book tells more than CNN can tell without risking to be ripped to pieces for not supplying bomb-tight evidence.<br /><br />Mainly unproven rumors? Not really! Hear-say, yes. Lots and lots of hear-say, and not all with evidence that would hold in court. But it is all hear-say from people who should know. And there is no reason why either these insiders or the author should have lied. There is also something else: Taking the contents of this book in context with what I keep hearing from Trump himself on the daily news, I can only say that all this hear-say fits like pieces into a picture puzzle. For all these reasons, I believe every word of this book. <br /><br />I cannot help myself, but I have to compare this book to a colonoscopy—a colonoscopy that ventures into the intestines of the Trump White House, finding unhealthy growths, numerous parasites, and pathologic microbes (more and more outnumbering beneficial critters), while encountering various other ass-crawlers and here and there a piece of shit. To stay with this analogy: Amidst of all these undesirable colon contents is a big undigestible and toxic something that should have never landed there and that is not only causing cramps and constipation but might prove fatal to the whole organism (that is, our country or even our planet) unless this big troublemaker can be expelled with the help of a strong laxative or an enema (aka impeachment). Sorry if I should have made you feel nauseated. Yet weren’t you already feeling nauseated when you watched the news today?<br /><br />Before I go, I would like to tell you a little story:<br /><br />Back in Germany, we had a neighbor. He was a real jerk. If the word "jerk" hadn't existed, it would have had to be invented for this guy. The only reason his wife (our cleaning lady) did not divorce him was because she would have ended up on welfare after a divorce. This guy had the brains of a soda biscuit. He was what my husband and I call "a brainless horned toad". Whatever he did was stupid and would result in some kind of damage. He, of course, also squandered money, leaving his wife in quite a predicament. Besides, every time this guy would open his big mouth, everyone around him could hardly wait for him to shut up again. Obviously, this guy had never heard of Kurt Tucholsky's famous words: "Gepriesen seien die Menschen die nichts zu sagen haben und dennoch den Mund halten. (Praised be those people who have nothing to say and keep their mouths shut in spite of this.)”—And guess what! Ever since inauguration day in January 2017, hardly a day goes by that my husband and I don't remind each other that this guy would have made so much better a President than what we have now in the White House. <br /><br /><br />UPDATE April 29, 2018:<br /><br />While reading this book, I kept thinking: ‘The idiocy and lunacy of this President and the nasty battles between the different alliance groups in the White House can’t get any worse.’ only to find out on the next pages that they did get worse.<br /><br />Re our President’s ethics and morals, you’ll find nothing more telling than the following excerpt:<br /><br /><blockquote>“Trump liked to say that one of the things that made life worth living was getting your friends’ wives into bed. In pursuing a friend’s wife, he would try to persuade the wife that her husband was perhaps not what she thought. Then he’d have his secretary ask the friend into his office; once the friend arrived, Trump would engage in what was, for him, more or less constant sexual banter. ‘Do you still like having sex with your wife? How often? You must have had a better fuck than your wife? Tell me about it. I have girls coming in from Los Angeles at three o’clock. We can go upstairs and have a great time. I promise …’ And all the while, Trump would have his friend’s wife on the speakerphone listening in.”</blockquote><br />Re our President’s and his family members’ ethics and intelligence, you will probably find this following excerpt of Bannon’s account of the Trump Tower meeting with the Russians enlightening:<br /><br /><blockquote>“The three senior guys in the campaign thought it was a good idea to meet with a foreign government inside Trump Tower, in the conference room on the twenty-fifth floor—with no lawyers. They didn’t have any lawyers. Even if you thought that this was not treasonous, or unpatriotic, or bad shit, and I happen to think it’s all of that, you should have called the FBI immediately. Even if you didn’t think to do that, and you’re totally amoral, and you wanted that information, you do it in a Holiday Inn in Manchester, New Hampshire, with your lawyers who meet with these people and go through everything and then they verbally come and tell another lawyer in a cut-out, and if you’ve got something, then you figure out how to dump it down to Breitbart or something like that, or maybe some other more legitimate publication. You never see it, you never know it, because you don’t need to. … But that’s the brain trust that they had.”</blockquote><br />No further comment. <br /><br />There is this old saying: “America is the land of unlimited possibilities. Here a dishwasher can become President.” Well, I don’t know of any dishwasher ever having become President of the United States. However, we can safely say now: “America is the land of unlimited possibilities. Here an incompetent, illiterate, ill-tempered, immoral, imbecile can become President.” However, if he’ll be able to stay President, remains to be seen.<br /><br /><br />P.S. Let’s not give up. We, The People, can still speak up. We, The People, can still vote. We, The People, can still march in protest, call our representatives in Congress, and do whatever else citizens of a democracy can legally do. Please note that I say “still”. Once our democracy will have been destroyed and replaced with an evil dictatorship, it will be too late.—I urge everyone to read the above book, just as I urge everyone to read “The Making of Donald Trump”, by David Cay Johnston, and “On Tyranny: Twenty Lessons of the Twentieth Century”, by Timothy Snyder.<br /><br /><br />UPDATE February 24, 2019:<br /><br />Please also read "It's Even Worse Than You Think", by David Cay Johnston, and "Everything Trump Touches Dies", by Republican (!) strategist Rick Wilson.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2944332304260588372" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


