    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2291766486" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2291766486" />
    <a title="Always Pouting" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48650982-always-pouting"><img alt="Always Pouting" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483476563p2/48650982.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2291766486?book_show_action=true">Feb 11, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Always Pouting" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Always Pouting" href="/user/show/48650982-always-pouting">Always Pouting</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2291766486" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13986287336418281232">Oh dear how do I even go about reviewing this book. I know politics is something we all get fired up about so I just want to say that anything I say is my own personal opinion and I&apos;m totally open to alternative perspectives if someone wants to respond in the comments, but if you&apos;re just going to call me a libcuck or whatever don&apos;t bother. I was actually pretty excited to read this and put a hold on it over on my library through overdrive and even though I have a huge pile of work, I decided to </span>
  <span id="freeText13986287336418281232" style="display:none">Oh dear how do I even go about reviewing this book. I know politics is something we all get fired up about so I just want to say that anything I say is my own personal opinion and I'm totally open to alternative perspectives if someone wants to respond in the comments, but if you're just going to call me a libcuck or whatever don't bother. I was actually pretty excited to read this and put a hold on it over on my library through overdrive and even though I have a huge pile of work, I decided to just spend hours reading it because my turn to have it came up. Of all the books that have been written so far this year about the presidency, this one elicited the most ire and strongest reaction from our president and of course I really just wanted to see what the big deal was. <br /><br />And honestly I have to say that I'm a little disappointed after reading it. The administrations reaction to the book made me think there was some new shocking revelation in the book but really it just confirms all the other reports we have been seeing about the white house anyways. The only new thing that seemed to come out of this book was the idea of using the 25th amendment to get rid of Trump, and this was brought up multiple times by Bannon, which just makes it feel like Bannon's own maneuvering to help put that idea out there honestly. Like no one was really talking about that before the book came out so like good one Steve. <br /><br />The rest of it though, the constant disarray and lack of cohesive strategy is pretty clear to anyone who keeps tabs on politics. There are really only a few things in the book that seem ridiculous and like Wolff was exaggerating like Trump's fear of being poisoned, or when he tries to lay out people's intentions and ambitions. Wolff clearly can't read people's minds so he cant tell us those things with certainty and I'd take it all with a grain of salt. The whole thing corroborates what has been leaking for months, even the fact that things have been leaking from higher up for months. If anything good has come out of this book it's that I see less of Steve Bannon now that he's been dumped by Donald for running his mouth through out the book. <br /><br />It does seem that Steve may have done that on purpose and that he seems to think that he's more powerful than Trump, and so he doesn't care that he's out on his own. I just think that Trump and Bannon are both being self centered in thinking they have some magically understanding that gives them credit with the people voting for Trump. It really just seems to me like most people are sick of the government and were trying to get someone new in because they are dissatisfied with how things are going which is the larger feeling that gets people like Trump elected. It's the same thing underpinning the tea party and people who elected Obama, like a lot of people just don't like how our government is being run and want someone new to come in and try harder. I know there are differences in exactly how people think that should be done policy wise but it does seem like people are much more flexible on that side of things, like the freedom caucus has basically fallen in line with Trump right, so much for all the deficit nagging. <br /><br />The whole situation is just ridiculous honestly, like why does Trump have such a burning need to be liked when he's literally in the highest office in the country. Also why does the media then turn around and indulge him in it. Honestly the amount of outrage and emotion being directed at Trump just saying dumb things seems like a waste of time when we all know he doesn't have anything to back up his talk. We should really be paying attention to what's actually happening on the policy side because I don't think the people who voted for him would be happy about any of the actions that have been going through congress while Donald runs around tweeting about little rocket man. Trump ran on a rather leftist style platform and no one is going to approve of the things they're doing to things like the FCC or the tax cut. <br /><br />So while this book is amusing and just confirms the disaster this administration is and the rampant delusion running amok, it really again doesn't do much about the problems were going to be left with after he's gone. If you just want to be amused about how crazy it all is totally go ahead and pick it up but it really doesn't shed any new light on things. It's just another frustrating book highlighting the fact that this inane bullshit is taking away people's energy to focus on all the actual things he's fucking up like appointing so many young right wing judges to federal court or deporting people mindlessly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13986287336418281232" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


